\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Chromatography as Partition Lag.} (\textbf  {A}) Three-dimensional transport parameter space: partition lag $\tau _p$ (ns), cyclotron frequency $\omega _c$ (MHz), and compression cost ($k_BT$) for 70 proteomics ions. Spike protein ions (red) and lactoferrin ions (blue) form distinct clusters reflecting their different mass ranges. The clustering along the compression cost axis near 47~$k_BT$ confirms the universality of the Landauer-limited volume reduction. (\textbf  {B}) Partition lag $\tau _p$ vs.\ precursor $m/z$, demonstrating that chromatographic retention time is a direct function of partition state: $t_R = \tau _p(S_k, S_t, S_e)$. The positive correlation confirms that heavier ions experience longer partition lag, consistent with the Penning-trap model of the chromatographic column as a trap array. Lactoferrin glycopeptides (blue, $m/z$ 1,216--2,717) exhibit systematically larger $\tau _p$ than spike protein glycopeptides (red, $m/z$ 903--1,334). (\textbf  {C}) Compression cost distribution for the $10^{21}\times $ volume reduction (mL injection $\to $ nm$^3$ droplet). Both datasets cluster tightly around a mean of 47.3~$k_BT$ (dashed line), consistent with Landauer's principle applied to 68 bits of erased spatial information. The narrow distribution confirms that compression cost is an intrinsic property of the partition transformation, independent of analyte identity. (\textbf  {D}) Cyclotron frequency $\omega _c$ vs.\ precursor $m/z$, overlaid with the theoretical curve $\omega _c = qB/m$ for $B = 7$~T (solid line). Both datasets follow the expected inverse-mass relationship, confirming that the partition Lagrangian coupling $\mu = \alpha (m/z)$ correctly reproduces the ion cyclotron resonance frequency within the chromatographic trap array.}}{16}{figure.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:chromatography}{{6}{16}{\textbf {Chromatography as Partition Lag.} (\textbf {A}) Three-dimensional transport parameter space: partition lag $\tau _p$ (ns), cyclotron frequency $\omega _c$ (MHz), and compression cost ($k_BT$) for 70 proteomics ions. Spike protein ions (red) and lactoferrin ions (blue) form distinct clusters reflecting their different mass ranges. The clustering along the compression cost axis near 47~$k_BT$ confirms the universality of the Landauer-limited volume reduction. (\textbf {B}) Partition lag $\tau _p$ vs.\ precursor $m/z$, demonstrating that chromatographic retention time is a direct function of partition state: $t_R = \tau _p(S_k, S_t, S_e)$. The positive correlation confirms that heavier ions experience longer partition lag, consistent with the Penning-trap model of the chromatographic column as a trap array. Lactoferrin glycopeptides (blue, $m/z$ 1,216--2,717) exhibit systematically larger $\tau _p$ than spike protein glycopeptides (red, $m/z$ 903--1,334). (\textbf {C}) Compression cost distribution for the $10^{21}\times $ volume reduction (mL injection $\to $ nm$^3$ droplet). Both datasets cluster tightly around a mean of 47.3~$k_BT$ (dashed line), consistent with Landauer's principle applied to 68 bits of erased spatial information. The narrow distribution confirms that compression cost is an intrinsic property of the partition transformation, independent of analyte identity. (\textbf {D}) Cyclotron frequency $\omega _c$ vs.\ precursor $m/z$, overlaid with the theoretical curve $\omega _c = qB/m$ for $B = 7$~T (solid line). Both datasets follow the expected inverse-mass relationship, confirming that the partition Lagrangian coupling $\mu = \alpha (m/z)$ correctly reproduces the ion cyclotron resonance frequency within the chromatographic trap array}{figure.6}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Cross-Laboratory Partition Consistency: Spike Protein Source Libraries A--K.} (\textbf  {A}) Three-dimensional S-entropy space $(S_k, S_t, S_e)$ for 600 randomly sampled entries from 4,455 glycopeptide records across 11 independent source laboratories, colored by source. All sources populate overlapping regions of the entropy cube, demonstrating that partition coordinates are intrinsic to the analyte, not dependent on the particular laboratory or instrument. (\textbf  {B}) Number of validated glycopeptide entries per source laboratory (A--K), ranging from 268 (Source E) to 579 (Source K). Despite varying library sizes, all sources achieve 100\% partition coordinate validity. (\textbf  {C}) Precursor $m/z$ distribution by source laboratory. Each source spans a comparable mass range ($\sim $200--7,500~Da) with similar density structure, confirming sampling consistency across independent laboratories. The jittered scatter reveals the full dynamic range of the glycopeptide search space. (\textbf  {D}) Distribution of principal quantum number $n$ across all 11 sources. The overlapping histograms confirm that all laboratories recover the same partition shell structure, with the dominant population at $n = 3$--$4$ regardless of source.}}{16}{figure.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:source_libraries}{{7}{16}{\textbf {Cross-Laboratory Partition Consistency: Spike Protein Source Libraries A--K.} (\textbf {A}) Three-dimensional S-entropy space $(S_k, S_t, S_e)$ for 600 randomly sampled entries from 4,455 glycopeptide records across 11 independent source laboratories, colored by source. All sources populate overlapping regions of the entropy cube, demonstrating that partition coordinates are intrinsic to the analyte, not dependent on the particular laboratory or instrument. (\textbf {B}) Number of validated glycopeptide entries per source laboratory (A--K), ranging from 268 (Source E) to 579 (Source K). Despite varying library sizes, all sources achieve 100\% partition coordinate validity. (\textbf {C}) Precursor $m/z$ distribution by source laboratory. Each source spans a comparable mass range ($\sim $200--7,500~Da) with similar density structure, confirming sampling consistency across independent laboratories. The jittered scatter reveals the full dynamic range of the glycopeptide search space. (\textbf {D}) Distribution of principal quantum number $n$ across all 11 sources. The overlapping histograms confirm that all laboratories recover the same partition shell structure, with the dominant population at $n = 3$--$4$ regardless of source}{figure.7}{}}
