\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Bijective Transformation Validation.} (\textbf  {A}) Three-dimensional space of dimensionless numbers (Weber, Reynolds, Ohnesorge) for all 70 proteomics ions. Spike protein ions (red) and lactoferrin ions (blue) occupy distinct but physically valid regions: $\text  {We} = 1.9$--$3.3$, $\text  {Re} = 0.6$--$1.1$, $\text  {Oh} = 1.4$--$2.3$. The clustering confirms that the bijective transformation maps ions to thermodynamically consistent droplet states, with Weber numbers in the capillary-dominated regime and Reynolds numbers below unity (laminar flow). (\textbf  {B}) Round-trip reconstruction error (S-entropy $\to $ droplet $\to $ S-entropy) vs.\ precursor $m/z$. All 70 ions achieve reconstruction errors below $10^{-15}$ (machine precision), well below the bijective threshold of $10^{-10}$ (dashed line). The uniform distribution across the mass range confirms that bijective fidelity is independent of ion mass. (\textbf  {C}) Weber--Reynolds phase space colored by Ohnesorge number (viridis scale). The positive correlation between We and Re reflects the shared dependence on droplet velocity, while the Ohnesorge number encodes the viscous--surface-tension balance. The tight clustering within a physically meaningful region validates that the transformation produces realistic droplet parameters. (\textbf  {D}) S-entropy round-trip validation: original $S_k$ vs.\ recovered $S_k$ after the full bijective cycle. All points lie exactly on the identity line (dashed), confirming zero information loss. The transformation is bijective to machine precision for all 70 proteomics ions.}}{22}{figure.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:bijective}{{12}{22}{\textbf {Bijective Transformation Validation.} (\textbf {A}) Three-dimensional space of dimensionless numbers (Weber, Reynolds, Ohnesorge) for all 70 proteomics ions. Spike protein ions (red) and lactoferrin ions (blue) occupy distinct but physically valid regions: $\text {We} = 1.9$--$3.3$, $\text {Re} = 0.6$--$1.1$, $\text {Oh} = 1.4$--$2.3$. The clustering confirms that the bijective transformation maps ions to thermodynamically consistent droplet states, with Weber numbers in the capillary-dominated regime and Reynolds numbers below unity (laminar flow). (\textbf {B}) Round-trip reconstruction error (S-entropy $\to $ droplet $\to $ S-entropy) vs.\ precursor $m/z$. All 70 ions achieve reconstruction errors below $10^{-15}$ (machine precision), well below the bijective threshold of $10^{-10}$ (dashed line). The uniform distribution across the mass range confirms that bijective fidelity is independent of ion mass. (\textbf {C}) Weber--Reynolds phase space colored by Ohnesorge number (viridis scale). The positive correlation between We and Re reflects the shared dependence on droplet velocity, while the Ohnesorge number encodes the viscous--surface-tension balance. The tight clustering within a physically meaningful region validates that the transformation produces realistic droplet parameters. (\textbf {D}) S-entropy round-trip validation: original $S_k$ vs.\ recovered $S_k$ after the full bijective cycle. All points lie exactly on the identity line (dashed), confirming zero information loss. The transformation is bijective to machine precision for all 70 proteomics ions}{figure.12}{}}
